Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Cut the @medium tomato{1}(cut into 2cm chunks) into 2cm chunks. Drain and rinse the @lentils{1} in a #sieve{}.

Zest and halve the @lime{1/2}(zested and halved).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{260%g} and onion to the saucepan and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Cook until the chicken is browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}. Turn occasionally. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Next, add the @pasanda style seasoning{1}, lime zest and garlic. Stir-fry for ~{1%minute} more.

Stir in the @coconut milk{200%ml}, lentils, @vegetable stock paste{15%g} and @water for the soup{200%ml} until combined.

Bring the soup to the boil, then reduce the heat to low and simmer until slightly thickened, ~{6-8%minutes}. Cook until the chicken is cooked through. IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once thickened, stir through the tomato and @baby spinach{40%g} a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once the veg has been added to the soup, cut the @plain naans{2} in half widthways, then put in your #toaster{} until golden.

Once toasted, generously spread the @butter{10%g} over the naans.

Once the soup has thickened slightly, stir through the @mango chutney{40%g} and a squeeze of lime juice.

Season to taste with salt, pepper and more lime juice if needed. Remove from the heat.

Share the lentil soup between your #bowls{}.

Serve with the buttery naans alongside.

Enjoy!